key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.AllowOwnPeerForComponentDrawable
key.description:
Defines, that components drawn in a Component-Element or a ComponentDrawable are allowed to supply their own window-object as native peer. Allowing foreign peers can lead to very strange behaviour, ranging from unpredictable effects in the UI of the calling programm to even memory leaks.
This property defaults to false.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.ComponentDrawableMode
key.description:
Defines how the system processes AWT-components. Possible values are:
'private' - All components get their own peer. This may result in problems on Windows. If you receive the message 'No more handles available', switch back to 'shared' mode.
'synchronized' - All components get their own peer, but all drawing operations will be executed on the AWT-EventDispatcher thread. This may result in problems on Windows. If you receive the message 'No more handles available', switch back to 'shared' mode.
'shared' - All components of a given report share a single AWT-peer. All drawing operations will be executed on the AWT-EventDispatcher thread.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.ConfigStore
key.description: Selects which implementation is responsible for storing configuration information.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.DebugDataSources
key.description: Defines whether datasources should provide additional log messages. This logging can also be used to measure the execution time of queries. As this kind of logging can result in large amounts of data it is set to 'fase' as default. Set it to 'true' to enable the logging.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.DynamicStrokeDashes
key.description:
Defines, whether the stroke dashs should take the pen width into account or whether the stroke dashes should always be static.
The static version was the default until JFreeReport 0.8.7-4 and has been changed to the more sensible dynamic model since that version.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.FixImageResolutionMapping
key.description:
Defines that the layouter uses the System's native resolution to compute the size of images. This fixes problems with the HTML output, which assumes that images are rendered with a resolution of 96dpi.
This setting defaults to true. To make use of it, the Device-Resolution configuration setting has to be defined as well.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.NoPrinterAvailable
key.description:
Defines, whether JFreeReport should query the default page format from the printerdriver. If there is no printer installed on Windows, this seems to block the JavaVM until a time out is reached.
If this property is set to "true" a hard coded default page format is used instead. By default, the engine assumes that a printer is available and therefore this property defaults to 'false'.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.StrictErrorHandling
key.description: Defines a stricter error handling, if set to 'true', then all errors that occur during the report processing will cause the report processing to fail. It is safe to set this to 'true', as valid reports never throw exceptions.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.URLEncoding
key.description: Defines the character encoding that is used when encoding text for URLs. This setting default to ISO-8859-1 as this is the common standard.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.WarnInvalidColumns
key.description:
Defines, whether the datarow prints warning on invalid columns. Requests to invalid columns are non fatal, but these messages give usefull hints on invalid report definitions.
If set to true, an additional logging entry is added whenever an invalid column is encountered.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.YieldRate
key.description:
Defines how often the report processing thread should yield to let other processes continue. Setting this property to a value greater than zero enables the Yield-feature and improves the overal reponsiveness of the application at the cost of some performance.
This property default to '100'. Set it to zero to disable yielding.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.layout.FooterPageBandMode
key.description:
Defines how the footer-bands of a pageable or flow-export should behave. If the band processing is set to 'slotted', a subreport's footer will stay active for the remainder of the page even if the subreport itself has been finished already.
'plain' - a footer is disbanded and removed from the page as soon as the report which generated it is finished. Therefore a subreport can never define the footer for the last page of the subreport.
'slotted' - a footer remains active beyond the lifetime of the subreport. The footer will be disbanded as soon as the page has been finished. In this mode, a subreport can define the page-footer for all the pages it appears on. (This setting is the default.)

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.layout.HeaderPageBandMode
key.description:
Defines how the header-bands of a pageable or flow-export should behave. If the band processing is set to 'slotted', a subreport's header may be active for the first page the subreport appears on in case the page's content area is still empty.
This mode of behavior differs from the behavior encountered in 0.8.9, but as it is more natural than the 'plain' mode, it is now the new default.
'plain' - headers are evaluated only during page-start events. Therefore a subreport can never define the page-header for the first page the subreport appears on.
'slotted' - Headers are evaluated and activated as long as the page's content area is empty and not other content has been printed yet. Therefore a subreport can contribute to the page-header of the first page it appears on. (Default)

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.layout.defaults.FontSize

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.layout.defaults.FontSmoothThreshold
key.description: Defines the minimum font size in point to which Text-Antialiasing is applied if the Font-Smooth property is set to auto. This setting defaults to '8' as smaller fonts tend become unreadable with aliasing applied to them.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.layout.fontrenderer.IsBuggyFRC
key.description:
This is a override setting. Some Graphics2D implementations have problems with the font positioning. I don't know a way to resolve that bug on the root, so if the bug happens to you, try setting this property to "true" to resolve wrong or buggy string draw results.
(This property is no longer used.)

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.layout.fontrenderer.UseAliasing
key.description:
Enable aliasing for Graphics2D. This may result is textlayout errors. If your text is not correctly aligned, disable this property.
(This property is no longer used.)

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.layout.fontrenderer.UseMaxCharBounds
key.description:
The old JFreeReport way of computing line heights is not working correctly in some cases. Under some conditions, a character may exceed its normal line height (for instance if it is an upper case letter with accents). In that case, using the font size as line height is not working correctly, causing the text to be clipped.
If this property is set to 'true', the line height is computed from the maximum character size for the specified font. If set to 'false', the line height is set to match the declared font size, so that the old behaviour of previous versions of JFreeReport is preserved.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.pageable.graphics.DeviceResolution
key.description:
Defines in which resolution the generated images should be printed. If the image is not available in a suitable size for the given layouted output size, the image will be scaled to fit the specified device resolution.
For the sake of backward compatitibility, we define the device resolution to be 72 DPI. This way, a pixel equals a point in the rendering.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.pageable.graphics.UseNativeScaling
key.description:
Defines, whether scaling should use the device's native scaling, which may or may not produce sensible results, or whether the images should be prescaled using a internal image scaling algorithm.
This defaults to "false" so that we can guarantee the same output quality in all cases.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.pageable.graphics.WatermarkPrinted

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.pageable.graphics.debug.OutlineMode
key.description: Defines that the Graphics2D and PDF output will ignore the regular border and background definitions. The output target will draw debugging borders instead, which can be used to visualize the internal structure of the output. Unless you want to debug the report layouter, there is no need to enable this property.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.pageable.graphics.debug.PrintPageContents
key.description: Defines, that the output target will dump the currently processed page to the log system. This is expensive and creates huge amounts of data. It only makes sense to activate this property, if you are debugging the report layout system. For everyone else, activating this property will result in a enormous slow-down.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.pageable.pdf.DeviceResolution
key.description: Adjusts the resultion of the images embedded in the PDF. By default we use 150 DPI, which is slightly better than 72DPI and a good compromise between size and quality. For real high-quality printing you probably want to increase that to 300 or more.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.pageable.pdf.EmbedFonts
key.description: Defines whether to embed fonts in the generated PDF. This will result in larger PDF files, but makes sure that all characters are displayed properly.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.pageable.pdf.Encoding
key.description:
The default font-encoding for the OutputTarget. Can be changed with PDFOutputTarget.setFontEncoding for the specific instance if needed.
The encoding can also be defined on a per-element level.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.pageable.pdf.Encryption
key.description:

Access restrictions have no effect if the document is not encrypted, and not all security settings are active on 40-Bit encryption.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.pageable.pdf.OwnerPassword
key.description:
Defines the OwnerPassword for the PDF document. The owner has all perfmissions on the document and will be able to change the security settings.
Warning: Specifying passwords in the property file can introduce a security risk. Do not use these settings on the client side or in unprotected (world-readable) server environments. In these cases use other means of defining the password.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.pageable.pdf.Title

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.pageable.pdf.UseNativeScaling

Setting this property to 'true' can result in smaller PDF file sizes.

Warning: Specifying passwords in the property file can introduce a security risk. Do not use these settings on the client side or in unprotected (world-readable) server environments. In these cases use other means of defining the password.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.support.itext.AutoInit
key.description:
Defines, whether and how to register the fonts installed on that system. This will search the installed fonts on well-known locations based on the detected system environment.
Lazy font registration will defer the registration process until the font factory is first used. If the registration is defined to happen on init, the fonts will be registered as soon as the module get active for the first time.
The automatic registration can be disabled by setting this configuration entry to "never". You will have to register the fonts manually before you start the output, or TrueType fonts will not be available.
Valid values are "onInit", "never" or "lazy".

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.table.base.DebugReportLayout
key.description: Defines, whether the table-laoyuter will create extensive debugging logs. This is a great help for debugging the layouter, but should be left disabled by default, as it greatly slows down the report processing.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.table.base.ReportCellConflicts
key.description:
Defines, whether the table writer will print debug messages listing all overlapping elements and commit points. This requires the reporting engine to maintain additional data-structures which consume a large amount of memory and are expensive in both computation time and memory usage. The messages are very detailed and therefore great to debug report definitions,
Due to the high costs, this property should be disabled in production environments. However, as this is the only way for new users to tell why table-reports seem to ignore elements due to overlaps, this property is set to true by default.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.table.base.StrictLayout
key.description: Defines whether a stricter, but more accurate layout algorithm should be applied. Setting this property to false will greatly reduce the table complexity.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.table.base.UsePageBands
key.description: Defines, whether the table-export should export the page-bands (page-header, page-footer, and repeating group-header and -footer).

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.table.base.VerboseCellMarkers
key.description:
Defines, whether the cell-markers used to track occupied cells should contain detailed information about the repot elements contained in the cells. If set to false, it will not be possible to tell what element participate in the overlap conflict. To ease debugging, this property is set to true by default.
Verbose cell-markers are expensive, so you might want to disable them in production environments.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.table.html.CopyExternalImages
key.description: Defines, whether images referenced by an HTTP, HTTPS or FTP URL are copied to the output or included directly.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.table.html.EmptyCellsUseCSS
key.description:
Defines, whether empty cells will be controled using CSS. If this is set to true, the Table get the style property "empty-cells: show" assigned and the otherwise required no-break-space entites will no longer be generated.
The Internet-Explorer is not able to use correct CSS2 yet - they never obeyed to standards anyway, so that's no surprise that this defaults to "false"..

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.table.html.Encoding
key.description: Defines the document encoding. If undefined, it defaults to the platforms default encoding.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.table.html.ExternalStyle
key.description:
Defines whether the report processing should generate external stylesheet files.
If disabled, then the style information will be added as inline-stylesheet in the header of the generated file. If this option is enabled the engine will be able to directly stream the generated content to the output repository.
Enabling external stylesheet files also enables the streaming mode, so that the generated content is written to disk immediately. However, as the reference to the CSS file will be sent to the browser before the full style is known, this will lead to subtle rendering errors when used to stream the page to the browser in web-environments.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.table.html.ForceBufferedWriting
key.description:
This setting can be used to fully disable the direct streaming of the generated content. All generated content will be held in memory until the report processing has been finished. Only if the report processing finishes successfully, the generated HTML content is written.
This can be necessary in Web-Environments where the user's browser would try to read the CSS file before the stylesheet has been fully generated.
Buffering the content may lead to OutOfMemory-Errors if the generated content is very large. However, most browsers have troubles rendering files that are larger than 20MB, therefore the browser usually fails first.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.table.html.InlineStyles
key.description:
This setting can be used to fully disable the generation of stylesheets. All style-information will be added directly to the generated elements. The resulting content will be larger, but the output can be streamed directly to the repository without using the content-buffering.
Inline styles are safe for streaming the content in Web-Applications, as the browser will not be tricked into accessing stylesheets before the style has been fully computed.
If "BodyFragmentCreation" is enabled, the engine always generates inline styles.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.modules.output.table.xls.CellWidthScaleFactor
key.description:
The scale factor for the cell width (a double value). The cell width of spreadsheet files depends on the font size of the font used to render the contents on the client system. As we can't know that size, we have to guess, and as with every guessing, this may or may not be correct.
Experience showed, that a scale factor of 50 is a good estamination to match the built-in default of 'Arial 10' used by Excel and POI.

key.name: org.pentaho.reporting.engine.classic.core.states.NullDataSourceHandling
key.description:
Defines how the engine behaves, if a data-factory returns null instead of throwing an exception if it cannot handle a query. The implementations of 0.8.9 illegally returned null and therefore several reports depend on the behavior that in that case an empty tablemodel is auto-generated.
For now, we will warn that this is illegal behavior. In the next version, we will switch the property from "warn" to "fail" enforcing the correct behavior by default.
